ChatGPT said:
Nice catch, Ajinkya! That error means you're trying to access e.salary, but Java doesn't recognize it â€” usually because:

You forgot to declare salary as a public field, OR

You're accessing it from outside the class, and the field is private

âœ… Solution 1: Make salary a public field
(Quick fix for practice/testing â€” not ideal in real apps)

java
Copy
Edit
public class Employee {
    public String name;
    public int age;
    public double salary;

    // constructor + toString()
}
âœ… Solution 2 (Recommended): Use a getter method
This is the best practice for Java (even during interviews):

java
Copy
Edit
public class Employee {
    private String name;
    private int age;
    private double salary;

    public Employee(String name, int age, double salary) {
        this.name = name;
        this.age = age;
        this.salary = salary;
    }

    public double getSalary() {
        return salary;
    }

    public String toString() {
        return name + " | " + age + " | " + salary;
    }
}
Then your sort code becomes:

java
Copy
Edit
employees.sort(Comparator.comparingDouble(Employee::getSalary).reversed());
