âœ… Topic 1: synchronized vs volatile vs wait()/sleep()
ğŸ”¹ synchronized:
Prevents two threads from accessing the same critical section at the same time.

Can be used on:

Method (public synchronized void myMethod())

Block (synchronized(this) { ... })

ğŸ”¹ volatile:
Ensures changes made by one thread are visible to others.

Doesnâ€™t lock â€” just tells Java not to cache the variable per thread.

ğŸ”¹ sleep() vs wait():
Feature	sleep()	wait()
Belongs to	Thread class	Object class
Lock released?	âŒ No	âœ… Yes
Throws	InterruptedException	InterruptedException
Needs synchronized?	âŒ No	âœ… Yes
ğŸ’¡ Code Snippet:
java
Copy
Edit
public class SyncExample {
    private static int counter = 0;

    public static synchronized void increment() {
        counter++;
    }

    public static void main(String[] args) throws InterruptedException {
        Thread t1 = new Thread(() -> {
            for (int i = 0; i < 1000; i++) increment();
        });

        Thread t2 = new Thread(() -> {
            for (int i = 0; i < 1000; i++) increment();
        });

        t1.start();
        t2.start();

        t1.join();
        t2.join();

        System.out.println("Final counter: " + counter); // Should be 2000
    }
}
