Awesome, Ajinkya! Letâ€™s break down Topic 1 of Day 2: HashMap vs ConcurrentHashMap â€” this is a hot favorite in interviews when they want to test your concurrency knowledge ğŸ’¥

ğŸ” HashMap vs ConcurrentHashMap
âœ… HashMap
Feature	Value
Thread-safe?	âŒ No
Null Keys	âœ… 1 null key allowed
Behavior on Modification During Iteration	âŒ ConcurrentModificationException
Performance	Fast but not safe in multi-threaded env
ğŸ’¥ Example (Fails in multi-threaded context):
java
Copy
Edit
Map<String, String> map = new HashMap<>();
map.put("A", "Apple");
map.put("B", "Banana");

for (String key : map.keySet()) {
    map.put("C", "Cherry");  // ğŸ’£ Throws ConcurrentModificationException
}
âœ… ConcurrentHashMap
Feature	Value
Thread-safe?	âœ… Yes (internally uses segment locking)
Null Keys	âŒ Not allowed
Behavior on Modification During Iteration	âœ… No Exception (Fail-safe)
Performance	Very fast in concurrent scenarios (no full locking)
âœ… Example (Works perfectly):
java
Copy
Edit
Map<String, String> cmap = new ConcurrentHashMap<>();
cmap.put("A", "Apple");
cmap.put("B", "Banana");

for (String key : cmap.keySet()) {
    cmap.put("C", "Cherry");  // âœ… No exception
}
ğŸ’¡ Internal Difference:
HashMap â†’ One big unsafe structure, no thread safety.

ConcurrentHashMap â†’ Internally divided into segments (in older versions) or buckets (in Java 8+), with fine-grained locking to allow safe concurrent access.

ğŸ”¥ Interview Question:
"What if I use Collections.synchronizedMap(new HashMap<>()) instead of ConcurrentHashMap?"

âœ… It becomes thread-safe,
âŒ But iteration still throws ConcurrentModificationException,
because itâ€™s only synchronized, not fail-safe.

âœ… Your Practice:
