âœ… Day 2 â€“ Topic 2: synchronized vs volatile vs wait() vs sleep()
These are the building blocks of Java concurrency, and interviewers love asking tricky scenarios around them ğŸ”§

ğŸ§  1. synchronized
Used to prevent race conditions â€” only one thread can enter a critical section at a time.

âœ… Example:
java
Copy
Edit
public class Counter {
    private static int count = 0;

    public static synchronized void increment() {
        count++;
    }

    public static void main(String[] args) throws InterruptedException {
        Thread t1 = new Thread(() -> {
            for (int i = 0; i < 1000; i++) increment();
        });

        Thread t2 = new Thread(() -> {
            for (int i = 0; i < 1000; i++) increment();
        });

        t1.start();
        t2.start();
        t1.join();
        t2.join();

        System.out.println("Final Count: " + count); // âœ… Should print 2000
    }
}
ğŸ”¥ 2. volatile
Used when multiple threads are reading/writing a shared primitive variable.

It ensures:

Visibility of changes across threads

But no locking or atomicity

âœ… Example:
java
Copy
Edit
class Shared {
    public volatile boolean flag = true;
}
ğŸ”„ 3. wait() vs sleep()
Feature	sleep()	wait()
Defined in	Thread	Object
Releases monitor?	âŒ No	âœ… Yes
Used for	Pausing for time	Coordination between threads
Must be in synchronized block?	âŒ No	âœ… Yes
âš ï¸ wait() Must Be Inside synchronized:
java
Copy
Edit
synchronized(obj) {
    obj.wait();  // âœ… Valid
}
ğŸ”¥ Quick Interview Traps:
Can volatile make a method thread-safe?
âŒ No â€” it only ensures visibility, not atomicity.

Can we use wait() without a synchronized block?
âŒ No â€” it will throw IllegalMonitorStateException.

