ChatGPT said:
Awesome! Let's write code for both synchronized and volatile so you feel the difference in behavior âš™ï¸

âœ… 1. synchronized â€“ Safe Increment with Threads
java
Copy
Edit
public class SyncCounter {
    private static int count = 0;

    public static synchronized void increment() {
        count++;
    }

    public static void main(String[] args) throws InterruptedException {
        Thread t1 = new Thread(() -> {
            for (int i = 0; i < 1000; i++) increment();
        });

        Thread t2 = new Thread(() -> {
            for (int i = 0; i < 1000; i++) increment();
        });

        t1.start();
        t2.start();

        t1.join();
        t2.join();

        System.out.println("Final Count: " + count); // Should be 2000
    }
}
ğŸ§  Here, synchronized ensures only one thread modifies count at a time.

âœ… 2. volatile â€“ Shared Flag Between Threads
java
Copy
Edit
public class VolatileDemo {
    private static volatile boolean running = true;

    public static void main(String[] args) throws InterruptedException {
        Thread t1 = new Thread(() -> {
            while (running) {
                // Just keep looping
            }
            System.out.println("Stopped by main thread!");
        });

        t1.start();

        Thread.sleep(1000);  // Main thread sleeps for 1 second
        running = false;     // Set flag to false
        System.out.println("Main thread updated flag.");
    }
}
ğŸ§  Without volatile, the thread may never see the updated value due to caching.

