You said:
What is a singleton 
ChatGPT said:
Great question, Ajinkya â€” letâ€™s break it down from the basics:

âœ… What is a Singleton in Java?
A Singleton is a design pattern that ensures only one object of a class is ever created during the application lifecycle â€” and it provides a global access point to that instance.

ğŸ“¦ Real-Life Analogy:
Think of:

A printer spooler â€“ one per system

A DB connection manager

A Logger â€“ logs everything app-wide

You donâ€™t want 10 different loggers messing up your logs. You want one central object.

ğŸ§± Basic Singleton Structure:
java
Copy
Edit
public class MySingleton {
    // Step 1: Private static instance
    private static MySingleton instance;

    // Step 2: Private constructor
    private MySingleton() {}

    // Step 3: Public static method to get the instance
    public static MySingleton getInstance() {
        if (instance == null) {
            instance = new MySingleton();
        }
        return instance;
    }
}
You canâ€™t create new MySingleton() because the constructor is private

You get the instance using MySingleton.getInstance()

If it's already created, you get the same one â€” no duplicates

ğŸ”¥ Why Use Singleton?
Saves memory by reusing the object

Helps in managing shared resources

Prevents multiple access conflicts (like in logs or database connections)

