ChatGPT said:
Perfect! Letâ€™s dive into the Observer Pattern â€” itâ€™s a favorite for interviewers when they want to test your event-driven thinking.

âœ… Day 2 â€“ Topic 5: Observer Design Pattern
ğŸ“£ What is the Observer Pattern?
Itâ€™s a behavioral design pattern where:

One object (called the Subject) maintains a list of dependents (called Observers).

Whenever the subjectâ€™s state changes, all observers are notified automatically.

ğŸ§  Real-Life Analogy:
Think of a YouTube channel:

You (subscriber) = Observer

Channel = Subject

When the channel uploads a video â†’ all subscribers are notified!

âœ… Java Code Example
java
Copy
Edit
import java.util.*;

// Step 1: Observer interface
interface Observer {
    void update(String message);
}

// Step 2: Concrete observers
class EmailSubscriber implements Observer {
    public void update(String message) {
        System.out.println("Email received: " + message);
    }
}

class SMSSubscriber implements Observer {
    public void update(String message) {
        System.out.println("SMS received: " + message);
    }
}

// Step 3: Subject
class Publisher {
    private List<Observer> observers = new ArrayList<>();

    public void subscribe(Observer o) {
        observers.add(o);
    }

    public void unsubscribe(Observer o) {
        observers.remove(o);
    }

    public void notifySubscribers(String message) {
        for (Observer o : observers) {
            o.update(message);
        }
    }
}

// Step 4: Client code
public class ObserverDemo {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        Publisher channel = new Publisher();

        Observer user1 = new EmailSubscriber();
        Observer user2 = new SMSSubscriber();

        channel.subscribe(user1);
        channel.subscribe(user2);

        channel.notifySubscribers("New video uploaded!");
    }
}
âœ… Output:
less
Copy
Edit
Email received: New video uploaded!
SMS received: New video uploaded!
ğŸ”¥ Why Use It?
Decouples logic (Publisher doesnâ€™t need to know how notification works)

Easy to scale (add more observers without touching core code)

Event-driven systems love this pattern (think Kafka, messaging queues, etc.)

