Perfect, Ajinkya! Letâ€™s break down Microservices Communication â€” a must-know topic for any client interview.

âœ… Day 3 â€“ Topic 3: Microservices Communication
ğŸ”„ Why do microservices need to communicate?
Because each service is independent, but they often need data or trigger actions in others.

3 Major Ways Services Talk to Each Other:
Communication Type	Description	Tools/Tech
Synchronous	Request-Response model	REST (via RestTemplate / Feign)
Asynchronous	Event/message-driven	Kafka, RabbitMQ, ActiveMQ
Database-based	Shared DB (bad practice usually)	Avoid unless it's a legacy monolith
âœ… 1. Synchronous â€“ REST + Feign
ğŸ”¹ RestTemplate (Old way, still valid)
java
Copy
Edit
RestTemplate restTemplate = new RestTemplate();
String response = restTemplate.getForObject("http://order-service/orders/1", String.class);
ğŸ”¹ FeignClient (Clean, interface-driven)
java
Copy
Edit
@FeignClient(name = "order-service")
public interface OrderClient {
    @GetMapping("/orders/{id}")
    Order getOrder(@PathVariable Long id);
}
Requires Spring Cloud + Eureka/Service Discovery

âœ… 2. Asynchronous â€“ Kafka or RabbitMQ
Producer (sends messages)
java
Copy
Edit
@Autowired
private KafkaTemplate<String, String> kafkaTemplate;

public void send(String message) {
    kafkaTemplate.send("order-topic", message);
}
Consumer (listens for messages)
java
Copy
Edit
@KafkaListener(topics = "order-topic")
public void listen(String message) {
    System.out.println("Received: " + message);
}
Services are loosely coupled

Useful when order doesnâ€™t matter instantly (e.g., sending email after signup)

âœ… 3. Why Use Message Queue (MQ)?
Letâ€™s say:

Service A wants to inform B, C, and D something has changed

Instead of calling all 3 directly (tight coupling), it just puts a message on a topic

Whoever is interested (subscribed) will get it

ğŸ”¥ Common Interview Question:
"How do your microservices talk to each other?"

âœ… Say:

â€œWe use a combination of REST APIs for synchronous needs and Kafka for event-driven async communication. Feign helps simplify REST communication with other services registered in our service discovery layer like Eureka.â€

